commit_message:
jsonutils: simplify simple value handling

There's a few code duplications because for some reason the code
handling the recursive part got some conversion code for non-recursive
value.

Let's stack non-recursive value conversion as the top, and then use
"recursive" only where needed.

Change-Id: Ic1ecc76aba5402129a936dfb4649df0806a564a4

- check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/43/179043/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha/78d0c19/ : SUCCESS in 55m 43s'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-05-05 20:48:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Vladyslav, I'm a bit concerned about removing that check. We don't know what might call deploy_utils.deploy_partition_image() in the future, and/or whether whatever calls it, will call iscsi_deploy.check_image_size() first.

There's also a difference between iscsi_deploy.check_image_size() -- raises an exception, and the code in deploy_utils.deploy_partition_mage() -- uses the larger value.

So potentially, someone could write code that doesn't call iscsi_deploy.check_image_size() because they are OK with image_mb > root_mb, and want the code to default to using image_mb. It doesn't look like it is a huge expense to make this check either.

Anyway, you could be right and maybe it isn't needed and won't ever be needed. At the very least, there should be a comment in deploy_utils mentioning that it assumes that root_mb >= image_mb. [Having written this, if there is a comment, why not just leave the code there.]"}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-05-06 08:43:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Also we need to consider that this part of the code is going to be soon refactored into ironic-lib.  As it becomes a separate standalone library of it's own, auto-correcting root_mb might not be a right thing to do.  Rather we could throw an exception that we can't deploy an 8G image on a 5G root partition here.  But that said, the change might need to go in ironic-lib (or ported from here to there)."}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2015-05-06 10:15:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ruby, Ramakrishnan, thank you for your reviews.

Ramakrishnan, I agree, if someone would populate root_gb=5 in instance_info and would try to deploy 8gb image by calling directly deploy_partition_image then I think exception should be thrown, like it is done in iscsi_deploy.check_image_size. So, you think that it should go to ironic_lib? IIUC, these calls here would be at some point replaced by ironic_lib calls, so the behaviour will change anyway, right?

Ruby, what do you think about that?'}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-05-06 10:23:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Vladyslav, I am not sure about the plan of migration to ironic-lib. I think we might end up porting the commits on ironic for all the common files to ironic-lib.  Hence making change here might be appropriate. 

Also regarding the behaviour change, I think no one would have actually encountered this behaviour now because the code was solely in Ironic and wouldn't have got exercised because of the check before that in deploy.  Hence it should be okay in my opinion."}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2015-05-06 11:06:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-06 11:42:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Improve root partition size check in deploy_partition_image

There is a check in deploy_partition_image which ensures that size of
the image being deployed is greater than or equal to root partition
size. It is being checked on driver.deploy step by calling
iscsi_deploy.check_image_size by in-tree drivers, but if some
out-of-tree driver would use this function without calling
iscsi_deploy.check_image_size beforehand the logic would be
incorrect, as deploy_partition_image will silently change root_mb
value and proceed.

In this change it is proposed to throw an exception instead in this
case.

Closes-bug: #1454263

Change-Id: Iecd59d938762089ab639066fa994492a64e92937

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-12 19:28:30.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up logging to conform to guidelines

Correct instances where guidelines are not being followed.

Guidelines can be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Some of this is seen by folks implementing new code and results
in confusion during reviews. These are mostly trivial changes,
but the hope is this will provide good examples so as to avoid
that confusion.

Also cleaning up case of deprecated LOG.warn called in leiu of
LOG.warning as well as redundant cases of formatting an exception
inside of LOG.exception.

Change-Id: I7decb7bf5f3185f7d26ad99b0cb3475a88d3ec99
'}]
commit_message:
Clean up logging to conform to guidelines

Correct instances where guidelines are not being followed.

Guidelines can be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Some of this is seen by folks implementing new code and results
in confusion during reviews. These are mostly trivial changes,
but the hope is this will provide good examples so as to avoid
that confusion.

Also cleaning up case of deprecated LOG.warn called in leiu of
LOG.warning as well as redundant cases of formatting an exception
inside of LOG.exception.

Change-Id: I7decb7bf5f3185f7d26ad99b0cb3475a88d3ec99

commit_message:
Add partition number to list_partitions() output fields

Number of partition is important parameter.
Example: we have partitions 1,2,3,4 and partitions 2,3 removed.
Second partition has number 4 now, and we must know it for actions
via parted.

Change-Id: Ic6b6f39f53ea69562821a49fd6bf8ba9104e34c4

commit_message:
Fix security groups cleanup

In addition to the security groups that are explicitly created, Neutron
automatically creates a security group called "default" for each tenant.
We have to clean these up after destroying networks using the admin
context.

Co-Authored-By: Chris St. Pierre <cstpierr@cisco.com>
Change-Id: Ib8da1c608a3355cd2e08a7bc1a5aaa86444d1c39
Closes-Bug: 1355629

commit_message:
More fixes for UT

Some methods are now called more then the expected number, this
is not optimal but still logically correct

commit_message:
remove asterisk for optional fields in VPN forms

In VPN forms, the mandatory symbol is present in all the fields including optional fields.

This patch removed all the asterisk symbol for the optional fields.

Change-Id: Ie7930b8b27c72aaf3f9ca00bd72287c645f375d2
Closes-Bug: #1451383

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-12 22:49:27.000000000', 'message': 'Update ceph wizard page to controll all four options

Previously we only configured ceph for glance, or cinder, but this
excludes ephemeral or objects. Frequently deployers find this out
the hard way.

This changes the storage wizard page so that we either turn on all

commit_message:
Update ceph wizard page to controll all four options

Previously we only configured ceph for glance, or cinder, but this
excludes ephemeral or objects. Frequently deployers find this out
the hard way.

This changes the storage wizard page so that we either turn on all
ceph options or leave them all off (the default) and gives some improved
details about the impact of turning it on.

Change-Id: I73aeef0e6c7bb7d123d2086c90ba3d7289c0dc89
Closes-bug: #1454398

commit_message:
Execute "parted" from root in list_partitions()

Root rights is required for parted, even for printing partitions.

Change-Id: I12e763815723c6c708dc7ff7d4f5e4be2060423f

commit_message:
Integration test with addition and deletion of nodes.

- Deploy enviroment of vcenter+qemu with nova vlan, default backend for
  glance and with addition and deletion of nodes with different roles
- remove empty glance values from vcenter settings, since it is a default behaviour
- remove network verification
Change-Id: I9857b8a868b0a2db65dd2cbc89fdcf2b95e98a27
Closes-bug: 1444082

commit_message:
Add test to cover scenario from LP1426338

Add next scenario:
* Deploy ha environment with ceph
* Cretae instance, assign floating ip
* Ping instance
* Suspend rabbit-master controller
* Wait  while cluster becomes operable
* Ping created instance
* Suspend new master-rabbit controller
* Trurn on 1-st controller
* wait while cluster becomes operable
* Ping instance
* Turn on second offline controller
* wait while cluster becomes operable
* Ping instance
* Delete instance
* Run ostf

Change-Id: I78d93136d6b07cdf028bdb715fc8b2d35ece0cb1
Closes-Bug: 1427126

commit_message:
Use catalog=True for app_by_fqn helper function

app_by_fqn is used to query app images when building topology and during
updates of certain dynamic ui componenents. Both context might require
access to public apps from different tenants, therefore the function
should use catalog=True

Change-Id: I2ae4b5dfa55d72c1e384467afdcd64f4bd62ecf0
Closes-Bug: #1454674

commit_message:
Updated coverage related options to project

- Added .coveragerc file to project, this file is utilized
  to provide variuos various options like while running coverage.
- Used the .coveragerc file available in trove project.
- Updated tox.ini to show the calculated coverage results.

Change-Id: I9cc72766ab5a3ca48c60089062f37123dafc2850
Closes-Bug: #1453100
Closes-Bug: #1453101

commit_message:
Always create diagnostic snapshot atfer test.

- add a new environment variable:
    ALWAYS_CREATE_DIAGNOSTIC_SNAPSHOT, default = 'true'.

- move code that resume environment into a separate method.

- rename @log_snapshot_on_error to @log_snapshot_after_test

Change-Id: I5902899ba4c8557b7233e9bf576debc2197ca9e2
Closes-Bug:#1452672

Send packet out to the destination port and to destination DP (data path

always lost
Note:: Verified on one machine setup need to verify on multi host

commit_message:
Add possibility for devices with names like "xxxNNN.XXX"

to be not an 802.1q vlan interfaces
by defining

    vlan_dev: false

in network scheme

Change-Id: Ic2740c7187714c511fb7c58a10b173b65dda5d2b
Closes-bug: #1450420

(1 comment)

I like the idea. Only one little question inline.

@Qiming: I agree that probably all could be solved with regular expressions, but some of those will be complicated. So for many users, having pre-defined constraints available that can just be referenced by name will be easier to use.

Another question: This will also be applicable to parameter validation, right?'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-05-13 07:29:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

Could you please rename this spec to be more clear with content? I mean, that you add  only  network related constraints, but commit header and name of spec have more common words.'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-05-13 07:53:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Thomas, I agree that stricter validations are always a good thing to have. It will help filter out errors as early as possible. The thing that confuses me is to what extent these CustomConstraints will be useful. From a design perspective, we are enforcing some patterns and hoping them to be generic enough. From implementation's perspective, what we can do is still about string format checking, or, pattern matching.

I'm not a fan/expert of regular expression myself, but I do think some sample templates would be very useful already."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-05-13 09:36:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Qiming, these constraint can be done with regular expression but not easy to do so. Because IP and cidr both can be ip and ipv6 format.

And using a standard module is more easy to approach and elegant.

@Thomas, Yes, these constraint can be apply to parameters.

If you have better suggestion about what property should be constraint, it's welcome to comment here."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-05-13 10:01:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-13 10:10:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

to validate these inputs before stack create/update, so that users can get
an early error message.

Change-Id: I951aa216d073d86276113272a398faca9fbfbfd1
Implemented: blueprint enhance-property-constraints
"}]
commit_message:
Enhance neutron constraints

Since we have many type of properties, some of them have custom constraints,
e.g. nova.flavor, glance.image etc. But still some of them have some certain
format as input, e.g. IP address, MAC address, port, protocol etc. It's better
to validate these inputs before stack create/update, so that users can get
an early error message.

Change-Id: I951aa216d073d86276113272a398faca9fbfbfd1
Implemented: blueprint enhance-property-constraints

commit_message:
use binary filter to get compute services

In hypervisor, compute host tab, to get the list of nova-compute services.
We can use binary filter instead of getting all services and filter it locally.

Change-Id: Ib0e15e2cf77ef011c972192d0b57b9210adf37ab
Closes-Bug: #1454610

router internal ports. Patch, I7d4e8194815e626f1cfa267f77a3f2475fdfa3d1, adds
the necessary support for a legacy router.

For an HA router, instead of configuring the addresses on the router internal
ports we should be updating the keepalived config file and let keepalived
configure the addresses depending on the state of the router.

Following are the observations with the current code for an HA router.
1. IPv6 addresses are configured on the router internal ports (i.e., qr-xxx)
   irrespective of the state of the router. As the same IP is configured on multiple
   ports you will notice dadfailed status on the ports.
2. Keepalived configuration is not updated with the new IPv6 addresses.

This patch addresses the above issues for an HA Router.

Closes-Bug: #1446161
Partially-implements: blueprint multiple-ipv6-prefixes

commit_message:
Support multiple IPv6 prefixes on internal router ports for an HA Router

As part of BP multiple IPv6 prefixes, we can have multiple IPv6 prefixes on
router internal ports. Patch, I7d4e8194815e626f1cfa267f77a3f2475fdfa3d1, adds
the necessary support for a legacy router.

For an HA router, instead of configuring the addresses on the router internal
ports we should be updating the keepalived config file and let keepalived
configure the addresses depending on the state of the router.

Following are the observations with the current code for an HA router.
1. IPv6 addresses are configured on the router internal ports (i.e., qr-xxx)
   irrespective of the state of the router. As the same IP is configured on multiple
   ports you will notice dadfailed status on the ports.
2. Keepalived configuration is not updated with the new IPv6 addresses.

This patch addresses the above issues for an HA Router.

Closes-Bug: #1446161
Partially-implements: blueprint multiple-ipv6-prefixes
Change-Id: Icb9a0e4e6e5deafbdc0135ce7e6b100b1725df66

commit_message:
Allow unit tests to be run independently

Add various initializations and imports so that unit tests can be run
independently.

This change fixes the following test cases which could not be run
independently, that is running any individual unit test case by going
in to the py27 venv and running
"unit2 neutron.tests.unit.module.Class.test_case":

 neutron.tests.unit.plugins.ml2.drivers.arista.test_mechanism_arista.*
 neutron.tests.unit.plugins.ml2.drivers.cisco.apic.*
 neutron.tests.unit.plugins.ml2.test_rpc.RpcCallbacksTestCase.*
 neutron.tests.unit.services.l3_router.test_l3_apic.*
 neutron.tests.unit.agent.dhcp.test_agent.TestDhcpAgentEventHandler.*

(Note that these issues are not seen when running tox because the
initializations occur when all test modules are imported for test
discovery.)

Closes-bug: 1438463
Closes-bug: 1454640

Change-Id: I681caa66b51ce9a7bfbee5dfc43d534ba0d51947

commit_message:
Fix the KeyError in CloudByte iSCSI cinder driver

Driver returns KeyError during list TSM if there is no TSM
found in CloudByte Storage.
This patch will make driver to return proper message.

Change-Id: I77f137afc87b63c0b491e010a1b8ccf63e9e89c2
Closes-Bug: 1452642

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I387a7a1a817058a4daca313fe6df60612cb84864

commit_message:
Improved handling of endpoints missing urls

Currently if any of the interface urls (public, admin or internal) are
missing, audit middleware will break. This patch attempts to address
this issue.

Closes Bug: #1450868

Change-Id: Ic3484a81454a41b2a7e924f0bc23f854211cc513

commit_message:
Add a ceph job

This patch will allow us to create a job that uses Ceph
RBD for Nova, Cinder, and Glance.

For now we are making use of the fact that Ceph is
installed in the compute image. Eventually we'll
want to make use of a more flexible way to build
and load images within devtest (using either a single
image for everything, or building a new Ceph specific
image)

Change-Id: I22c9037fb734970396dd5045b8adf8a979bcf614
Depends-On: Id6a3fbc3477e85e8e2446e3dc13d424f9535d0ff
Depends-On: Ic47d028591edbaab83a52d7f38283d7805b63042

requirements.txt: Add ovs.

Add ovs to requirements.txt now that ovs is on PyPI.  Remove the hack
in the unit test related to this, as well.

While checking out rsync's man page, I noticed there's also the option --skip-compress, which defaults to skipping already compressed files. 

My concern with using --compress is that trying to use it on "already compressed" files might actually slow down the process. Since our data files don't have their true file extensions (eg., .zip or .jpg), I imagine using --skip-compress would not work. Is this a valid concern ??? Is there another way to figure out what files should not be compressed? Should we add a note to ops on the config file?'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-01-27 06:40:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

That's a very valid concern Thiago. I had came across it and should have mentioned it in commit message. It was one of the reasons why this option is configurable and off by default.

There are two theoretical fixes that I could think of. It's not worth the effort as it involves additional i/o.

1. Identify file by it's magic number (involves reading first few bytes of file!)

    >>> import magic
    >>> magic.from_file("/mnt/sdb1/./4/node/sdb4/objects/353/cd7/58482e05ea78310c6235c122e6e6acd7/1422340665.22984.data")
    'JPEG image data, JFIF standard 1.01, comment: "CREATOR: gd-jpeg v1.0 (using IJG JPEG v62), default quality"'
    >>> 

2. Read the 'name' key (to figure out extension) OR 'Content-Type' from dict stored in user.swift.metadata xattr.

commit_message:
Allow rsync to use compression

From rsync's man page:
-z, --compress
With this option, rsync compresses the file data as it is sent to the
destination machine, which reduces the amount of data being transmitted --
something that is useful over a slow connection.

A configurable option has been added to allow rsync to compress, but only
if the remote node is in a different region than the local one.

NOTE: Objects that are already compressed (for example: .tar.gz, .mp3)
might slow down the syncing process.

On wire compression can also be extended to ssync later in a different
change if required. In case of ssync, we could explore faster
compression libraries like lz4. rsync uses zlib which is slow but offers
higher compression ratio.

Change-Id: Ic9b9cbff9b5e68bef8257b522cc352fc3544db3c
Signed-off-by: Prashanth Pai <ppai@redhat.com>

commit_message:
User Guides: Enable translations

openstack-doc-tools 0.28 contains a fix for translation of RST guides
and the User Guides. Require that version and enable the User Guides for
translation.

Add building of glossary for translation environments to tox.ini.

Change-Id: I645bf98b68603811a9a978e508d1f492e44da738

commit_message:
Avoid creating temporary removal lists

Instead of creating a temporary list, only to then
iterate over it (and then never again use that temporary
list) just use itertools and create an iterator that we
use for iterating (therefore avoiding any need to create
a temporary list).

Part of ongoing blueprint make-things-speedy

Change-Id: I5322e5bdf613d485fbc8851c1319a907b425e2dd

commit_message:
Neutron: enable a voting py34 gate on master

With commit 8db41f04, "tox -epy34" is now successful in Neutron. Make sure it
stays that way by enabling a voting gate on the master branch.

Change-Id: I1e11c922d79fde4505904f83d477e23927504555

commit_message:
Add address format check for property

Some resource receive IP address as property, this patch adds
custom constraint for IP address format validation.

Implemented: blueprint enhance-property-constraints
Change-Id: Ie4ad71418aa355a4e24ac6c2a33bd85c19c5ef11

commit_message:
Move bandit requirement to test-requirements-bandit.txt

The deps in tox.ini wouldn't get updated automatically by the
openstack proposal bot. By moving the bandit requirements into
test-requirements-bandit.txt it will get updated automatically
when global-requirements changes.

Change-Id: Ifb0ec6ce4044adb38a1754521984f9900c612970

commit_message:
Remove unused jasmine_tests.py

The file openstack_dashboard/test/jasmine/jasmine_tests.py is not used;
it should be removed.

You can verify this by running the various tests:
  ./run_tests.sh --only-selenium
  or going to <host:port>/jasmine/ in a debug environment

Change-Id: Ieefaf30bfd5612bd3180b67817745a170596b1e5
Closes-Bug: 1454804

commit_message:
Recreation of tunnels and exception handling when adding vm port

The patch set handles recreation of tunnels
when openvswitch is restarted and it also proposes
the fix for exception thrown while adding vm port
after l2gateway connection to ovsdb

Closes-Bug:1452192
Closes-Bug:1452149

Change-Id: I3ccdd64272adc2d008da69fdd2652b029368fb44
Co-Authored-By: Phani Pawan <ppawan@hp.com>

commit_message:
Use greenthreads for mysql connections

This will patch the mysql python module to use greenthreads. This
allows us to avoid a deadlock situation where a greenthread will
be blocked trying to grab a mysql lock and not context switching
out.

Change-Id: Ic3d5afeb078323aaa2389254fb55b38d30f327cb
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
put retries on API calls known to deadlock

* There is a possible deadlock scenario in our plugin which
  can be fixed by retries. This is the issue:
    1) a plugin API call grabs the database transaction lock
    2) the plugin then block while making an HTTP call to the
       midonet server.
    3) another plugin API call comes in and tries to get the
       transaction lock, but times out because the other thread
       holds the lock.
* This is possible because neutrons threading implementation does not
  allow for context switching out of a thread that is blocked trying
  to obtain the DB transaction lock.
* This can be worked around by simply retrying calls that have timed
  out.

Change-Id: I70217e14cc14a93de2a5d7ec603882e2d0b67011
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
RAID URL handlers

Add basic handles for RAID configuration URL, as well
as basic tests for them.

They do nothing at this point and will serve as a staring
point for actual implementation.

Change-Id: Ie0727695590453376778ba9b0951f48c32286f34

commit_message:
fuelclient: node raid configration support

Add support for node RAID configuration. At this moment, download,
upload and apply actions for the confiration are supported, such as:

fuel --raid --node 1 {--download,--upload,--apply}

Change-Id: Icd35ed16998ef93f28478fd62b2098aa141234a0

commit_message:
nailgun: implement RAID default configuration

Introduce RaidManager responsible for generating
of the default RAID configuration for the nodes
based on its roles and available RAID controlles and
physical disks.

Change-Id: I5074eaa6a627fe6bff718ae13a78cafa81bcc7b4

commit_message:
nailgun: GET and PUT support for RAID API handler

 - Implement data model to store RAID configuration for a
   node
 - Implement API handlers to get and update RAID configuration
   for a node

This change modifies the database schema and the migration, so it
requires to run syncdb.

Change-Id: I995a31b04c14fb7f7e02306598ef7a5703e6d285

Add task manager for apply RAID config handler

Add a task which applies RAID configuration in
a fake mode.

Add an appropriate db migration, so the change
requires running syncdb.

commit_message:
agent: raid support

  - add raid detection
  - lsi parsing realization
  - delay bypass

1) Detecting hardware raid vendor
2) Realized lsi parsing and adding parsed information to data section
3) Also added the ability to skip random delay with sleep-off argument

Change-Id: Ia8d52c64109584f56aeb407b4f0e14e8eaea861e

commit_message:
Extenuate register_dhcp_agent code duplication in tests

Non-obvious changes:
* Change helpers.register_agent to use a slimmed down version
  of a plugin that knows how to register an agent. This allows
  the helper to be used with tests that do not register a core
  plugin.

Change-Id: Iefb1af676af6a984b01cdc1e9050541dffb5951a

commit_message:
UI change. Change on nodes tab

Changed page 'Configure Disks'. It added button switch between tab
'Disks' and tabs 'Raid Controller'. Tab 'Raid Controller' show all
virtual drives, HotSpare, NytroCache, CacheCade and unused disks
on this controller. Unused drives can be selected and added in new
virtual drives.

Change-Id: Ie9de1c74039a1b7c880e3520999a34f3405c5a44

[{'created': '2014-06-20 13:19:33.000000000', 'message': "Add new volume types

- image-cache type is for glance imag cache storag, that is mounted
  on /var/lib/glance/images-cache
- mysql is for mysql and is mounted on /var/lib/mysql

These volumes are optional, so set minimal size to 0. Also, make
'image' volume optional as well and set its minimal size to 0.

Change-Id: I0a376a9039d6d91dc167fa3869d530c736c0f6d1

commit_message:
Add new volume types

- image-cache type is for glance imag cache storag, that is mounted
  on /var/lib/glance/images-cache
- mysql is for mysql and is mounted on /var/lib/mysql

These volumes are optional, so set minimal size to 0. Also, make
'image' volume optional as well and set its minimal size to 0.

Change-Id: I0a376a9039d6d91dc167fa3869d530c736c0f6d1

commit_message:
Handle no disks in volume manager

During RAID configuration, it's possible that
we'll have no disks at all in the node metadata. So
handle that correctly without throwing an exception.

Change-Id: I48cd24d1cb064e5d4789ea77a65dc0a039fc7268

commit_message:
Remove skip of service-type management API test

Advanced services split is complete so remove the skip
for the service-type management API test.

(Yes, there is only one placeholder test. More tests
need to be developed.)

Also remove the obsolete 'JSON' suffix from the test
class.

Closes-bug: 1400370

Change-Id: I5b4b8a67b24595568ea13bc400c1f5fce6d40f28

commit_message:
Pass OS_* env vars fix for tox 2.0

Tox 2.0 stopped passing environment variables from the parent to
the tests, so the functional tests were failing since they rely
on keystone CLI getting the OS_* environment variables.

Change-Id: I4f05379df41a3f6ca24ce8eb6911144a381f058e

commit_message:
Remove common/ssh.py due to migration to tempest_lib

common ssh.py module and it tests was migrated to tempest_lib.
and included in tempest-lib release 0.5.0. This commit removes
the tempest copies of this module and switches over to using
the tempest-lib copy.

Change-Id: I4a38bd16b5568ce508623170eea186a3c53f1c89

commit_message:
Add capability to wait for IPv6 address in ip_lib

When an IPv6 address is added to an interface, it
goes into a tentative state for a couple of seconds
for duplicate address detection. During this time,
use of the address will fail. This is an issue for
functional tests where they may add an address to
an interface and then immediately run a ping and
expect success.

This patch adds a new wait_until_address_ready function
to ip_lib that will poll the interface every 200 ms until
the status transitions off of tentative or until a time limit
is exceeded. If the time limit is exceeded, it will raise an
exception.

It also adds unit tests and updates a functional test to
make use of the new feature.

Change-Id: I2fa51e3f55847f7b5062bec0c1c666f5c11364d5

commit_message:
Generate stack events for stack state transitions

Currently, the event-list output is very resource-centric, despite
being scoped to the stack from an API path perspective.

This, combined with the fact that the stack updated_at timestamp
is only updated after a succesful update (ref bug #1193269) makes
it impossible to derive the time when an update started via any API.

This is a problem when trying to use the new hook/breakpoint API,
because it's necessary to poll for all events since the most recent
update started, disregarding any stale hook events from previous
updates (which may have failed or timed out without the hooks getting
cleared).

To work around this, add an event for each stack state transition,
such that you can detect the transition to UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS,
then use that event as a marker to get post-update-started events.

Without this (or some other way to determine when the stack update
started), the hooks pre-update functionality landed for kilo is
not really usable (particularly mechanically via scripts).

Change-Id: Idff342b3aecc2d145dfbc7c0f610ad0ca8e52c8b
Partial-Bug: #1448155

Instead of creating a network in both the API cell and child cell,
let tempest use the old behavior of not querying networks from the
API for testing server create.

Change-Id: I9809d2b2e796ff1a5ea7e4f25bbeb21bd4817a72
'}]
commit_message:
Prevent setting tempest fixed_network_name for cells

Instead of creating a network in both the API cell and child cell,
let tempest use the old behavior of not querying networks from the
API for testing server create.

Change-Id: I9809d2b2e796ff1a5ea7e4f25bbeb21bd4817a72

commit_message:
Support multiple software config within one deployment

Change software deployment resource's config type to 'list',
and make one deployment support multiple software configs.

Change-Id: I9aa71a57232b05d00a780dba38ef1e1ccfe9dc03
Implements blueprint multi-software-config

commit_message:
Update docs and some files to remove kubectl.

Now that kubectl is not used in magnum, we need to update the docs.
This patch does the necessary changes.

Change-Id: I99067af163b51ef4ee279498d85c6bd223210e7a
Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

commit_message:
Fix doc issue of lock test accounts

When using the lock testing accounts, allow_tenant_isolation
should be set as False. Now it's missing in the document.
This patch will add it.

Closes-Bug: #1454001

Change-Id: I3e1e7a31ea4c1c8b25e821df545c8674a8de38da

commit_message:
setup port filters when sg rules change

when security group rules change, the l2 agents which have the
ports in this security group should reload iptables, this bug
was introduced by patch#118274.

Closes-bug: #1452718
Change-Id: Idb1577128be5d8812024467f599166bc131d57ea

commit_message:
Remove sahara from the default configuration

There is now a sahara specific tempest job. So sahara is no longer needed in
the default configuration of the integrated gate.

Change-Id: I7dc829fb0382c65b926b90f3a88843dd6495bb63
Depends-On: I1f89a4e6aa40250f5d036dcc98b59c0526e80995

commit_message:
Cinder: Set os_privileged_user credentials (for os-assisted-snapshots)

When calling os-assisted-snapshots APIs, Cinder often (by default) needs
 to pass an admin token to Nova. Currently it uses the credentials of
 the current user.

This will cause calls to Nova APIs for assisted volume snapshots to fail.

Configuration options should be added to specify different credentials
for talking to Nova.

Change-Id: I9e3ed53f4e1349d57a0c33518445f54ac63e36ec
Related-Bug: #1308736

commit_message:
Add a py34 env

Adds a new py34 environment in tox.ini which builds off of separate
(test-)requirements-py3.txt files that will just run flake8 for now
and an empty test-file.

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I5f00a96fc70613ca7014370ec826d0a6a6199fde

Posting my comments from the bug report here just in case they went unnoticed:

The fact that plug verifies that device exists is a characteristic of all the implementations of LinuxInterfaceDriver, where plug is actually abstract.

I agree that there is an unnecessary duplicate check here. I am ok with declaring that verifying that an interface exists before plugging is the responsability of the driver. This should be however documented, since in theory one could use his own custom driver (interface_driver is a configuration parameter).

Moreover since LinuxInterfaceDriver can use ip_lib perhaps the check should be done in the base class thus also removing some repeated logic in the various drivers.'}, {'account_id': 14615, 'date': '2015-02-09 08:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Refactor checks for device existence

The code calling driver.plug() shouldn't check for the device existence,
it's a duplicate and it's an expensive call.
Move check for device existence to base LinuxInterfaceDriver.plug()
to remove code duplication. Make plug_new() abstract instead.

Change-Id: Id118a64012ad10b197ba681ce5f1b2742eb135b4
Closes-Bug:1348703

[{'created': '2015-05-13 02:07:17.000000000', 'message': 'Fix function and test for 'trueorfalse'.

The function's comment is written as follow, however the function accepts
other values (ex. "e", "t", "T", "f", "F", etc...).

---
Accepts as False: 0 no No NO false False FALSE
Accepts as True: 1 yes Yes YES true True TRUE
---

Moreover if testval mach True or False, the function exits without resetting
xtrace.

Backported from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/181833/

This patch fixes the issue and add test patterns.

Change-Id: Ie48a859476faff22a4dfef466516e2d7d62ef0c0
Closes-bug: #1453687
'}]
commit_message:
Fix function and test for 'trueorfalse'.

The function's comment is written as follow, however the function accepts
other values (ex. "e", "t", "T", "f", "F", etc...).

---
Accepts as False: 0 no No NO false False FALSE
Accepts as True: 1 yes Yes YES true True TRUE
---

Moreover if testval mach True or False, the function exits without resetting
xtrace.

Backported from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/181833/

This patch fixes the issue and add test patterns.

Change-Id: Ie48a859476faff22a4dfef466516e2d7d62ef0c0

commit_message:
Added support of Kubernetes API in magnum.

This patch removes the use of Kubernetes CLI i.e kubectl
from magnum and adds the support of Kubernetes API.

Change-Id: Ibe7354abba962dde6855225471f468f6a19a41ff
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

subject: Support to import image to an existed volume
messages:
[{'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-05-08 09:27:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-08 09:29:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-cinder-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/39/181339/1/check/gate-cinder-specs-docs/1b09079//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 14s
- gate-cinder-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/39/181339/1/check/gate-cinder-specs-python27/3f4c2d3/ : SUCCESS in 1m 38s'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-05-08 11:59:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Copying an image to an attached volume is a terrible idea, there's no way for cinder to know if it is safe (I.E. Not mounted) and no advantage to doing so.

This leaves the usecase of overwriting an existent volume completely with a new image. This is completely the wrong way of thinking about volumes in the cloud - there's nothing special about a volume id, just create a new volume and delete the old one. Doing it in that order is also better from a data safety point of view - you can make sure the new volume works before losing the old one."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-05-11 06:51:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Duncan:
Yes,I got your point.But there is other case I think should consider: To support the rebuild of vm booted from bootable volume. Actually, it's a bug reported in this https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1378689, you can look at the commit about this bug. At now, it's can not change the image when rebuild the vm booted from bootable volume."}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-05-11 09:09:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Do the semantics of rebuild make sense when you're booting from a persistent volume?"}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-05-12 02:03:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Duncan:
I think you are right. It's no need persistence volume when rebuild vm. A new bootable volume is appropriate too. Well,I will abandon this idea. Thanks for your advice:)"}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-05-14 01:05:23.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

abandon this feature because it's not appropriate for cinder"}]

commit_message:
Support to import image to an existed volume

The purpose of this feature is to make user to quickly change
their operation system in the rootable volume.
No need to create a new volume from image and attach again
to vm.

blueprint support-to-import-image-to-an-existed-volume

Change-Id: Icfb51747dea1043a1714ae05961b180f6d55a95b

commit_message:
Set filesystem_store_datadir in tests

The new release of glance_store (0.5.0) included
I1d4f95cba47d21f1eb7e580314d01ac8d3481586, which raises errors if
filesystem_store_datadir or filesystem_store_datadirs is not set. Glance
currently is not correctly populating either of those options in certain
unit or functional tests, causing a lot of test failures. This patch
aims to unblock the gate by overriding the CONF option.

Change-Id: I3a9e0c7bfa4a9f38b41e93dce9652c4cc4811a9b
Closes-Bug: #1454384

commit_message:
Logging not using oslo.i18n guidelines (openstack)

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses
the openstack cinder directory. That directory is synced
from oslo, so no changes made. Translation markers are
being used, so this just removes the hacking check
exclusion of that directory.

Some cleanup of a couple files are also included in this
patch for other directories that had been previously
covered.

There have been quite a few instances found where the
i18n guidelines are not being followed. I believe this
has helped lead to some of the confusion around how to
correctly do this. Other developers see this code and
assume it is an example of the correct usage.

This patch attempts to clean up most of those violations
in the existing codebase to hopefully help avoid some of
that confusion in reviews.

Some issues address:
* Correct log translation markers for different log levels
* Passing format values as arguments to call, not preformatting
* Not forcing translation via six.text_type and others

Guidelines can be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Hacking checks will not be able to identify all violations of
the guidelines, but it could be useful for catching obvious
one such as LOG.info("No markers!").

Change-Id: If58a29c179e79e0b99e9da1d9a2ff1bc9c7b09e1
Closes-bug: 1433216
Closes-bug: 1431256

commit_message:
Don't autodoc the test suite

These are not public functions, pollute the existing docs, and extend
the time required to build docs.

A re-implementation of be1e94f

commit_message:
Cleanup docs landing page

Our docs our wildly out of date and pretty bad, this is a first step at
beginning to clean them up and make them more useful.

* remove the guidelines section. 2 of them are explicitly wrong (API
  Compatibility and Open Standards), and no one actually uses these
  guidelines during development. Yes we want high availability and fault
  tolerance, but listing these design guidelines here is misleading at
  best.
* Don't explain how this document is built, don't need to explain that
  so prominently
* Update the intro based on Nova's mission statement

Change-Id: Ia564a7cacdac0ddab913464ca1c7f9fefb0ee0b5

commit_message:
Use httpretty < 0.8.7 to avoid broken unittests

A hanging issue occurs with httpretty 0.8.7, 0.8.8 and 0.8.9
(so far) when running the units tests for
 openstack/python-ironicclient. This clamps the version to
< 0.8.7 since we don't know when/if this issue will be
addressed by httpretty.

The underlying issue appears to be tracked in this bug:
    https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/HTTPretty/issues/221

There is a proposed fix at:
    https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/HTTPretty/pull/193

Change-Id: I9767ff2129e85e4c94a079f4f8f981f4cdfa9b5b
Partial-Bug: #1454051

commit_message:
libvirt: deprecate the remove_unused_kernels config option

Commit 38997fc916904e47dcb847e1737eb26cbd38f6e1 added the option back in
grizzly with a note that it would be changed to the default behavior (or
removed) in the future.

The future is now!

DocImpact: The libvirt.remove_unused_kernels config option now defaults
           to True and is deprecated for removal in the 2016.1 release.

Change-Id: I82dff302cd9dead06fc27d145ee32b267984d323

commit_message:
Restart neutron-vpn-agent in l3_agent recipe when vpn is enabled

As there are some potential problems when neutron-l3-agent and
neutron-vpn-agent services are both running in the network node,
we should disable and stop neutron-l3-agent service.

The l3_agent recipe will be executed when running vpn_agent recipe,
so when firewall is enabled, restart neutron-vpn-agent service
instead of neutron-l3-agent service.

Closes-Bug: #1452121
Change-Id: I3d9ae89994770846094e24b3355ffad1a4e0d9ef

commit_message:
Create container json file under home directory

The current quickstart guide instructs user to create container.json
under current directory, which is not desired. Better to place
the file to home directory.

Change-Id: Ie357cc81e62d4016f009031114af5debff0dbc3b
Closes-Bug: 1454415

This is great, but I have to ask: what else is there in the "hz" namespace apart from "conf" and "framework". Why does everything have to be down under "framework"? Seems like an additional namespace for no real reason. What's the semantic difference between "hz" (the horizon ... framework) and "hz.framework"? :)

Not gonna block on this, but not gonna +1 it yet either.'}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-04-24 15:05:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

Thanks Richard!

Great question.

For me, the answer is that because openstack_dashboard also uses "hz.*" we want something in the common framework components name that makes it distinct from modules and components used for a specific UI.

Take a look at openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/launch-instance/launch-instance.js.

Its module is hz.dashboard.launch-instance. In this case "dashboard" is the equivalent of "framework". The framework level serves to group the horizon "common" components and keep them distinct from "hz.*" items that we create for specific UIs.

That way, as you are reading code in a specific UI (openstack_dashboard is the only one today), "hz.framework.api" is a hint that the APIs are from common code...but "hz.api" might not be clear if that comes from common or from dashboard.'}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-04-24 15:52:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

(7 comments)

Thanks Sean. Making suggested changes in next revision.'}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-04-24 16:05:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20.'}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-04-24 16:06:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20:

I'm looking for any suggestions you have on a better home for things like bind-scope and workflow which provide directives that modify UI behavior...but don't provide an element directive which may be what you consider a "widget"?'}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-04-28 00:37:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

Sean, great point about horizon/horizon and horizon/openstack_dashboard.

Let's talk more about this, but here was my reasoning. Components that live in horizon/horizon will have module names like "hz.widget.wizard" It is really nice if the directory structure is related "horizon/static/hz/widget/wizard".

"hz" therefore is the module root and tends to mean "things reusable by 2 or more horizon based UIs"

openstack_dashboard is one example of a horizon based UI. It seems odd to me (and Richard) that it too uses the "hz" prefix when it doesn't provide components that would be included in any other UIs (no other ones exists today).

I think it would be nice if the markup used something like "hzWizard" to indicate the generic wizard...but "osdWizard" to indicate it is some customized version of hzWizard provided by openstack_dashboard.'}, {'account_id': 13805, 'date': '2015-04-28 01:40:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 22:

I am fine with hz.something and dsb.something although I am not a big fan of it for sure. hz and dsb are not semantic at all. `hz` as a top level cap is normal in the industry, but having `hz` means framework and `dsb` as application or dashboard is really ugly for me. But again, I won't -1 for it.  

However, change namespace for workflow and bind-scope to hz.widget are hard to accept. They are not widgets sine there are no UI components created by them. widget means UI component. This was why their module names were designed like that. If we do not have a better sub namespace for them than the original one, then why bother changing?"}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-04-28 02:05:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

I like the split of hz and osd very much (where did "dsb" come from? I can't find reference to it anywhere except your comments, sean?)

As for workflow and bind-scope - I agree that placing them in widgets feels a little odd, but I can't offer a better suggestion that isn't some variation on "miscellaneous" which feels even more wrong. Sean, if you have a better suggestion let's hear it, otherwise how about we just go with widgets and change it down the track if a better solution comes up?'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-04-28 02:08:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

Oh, I guess we could retain "hz.framework" for the miscellanous stuff. Hmm.'}, {'account_id': 13805, 'date': '2015-04-28 02:25:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 22:

Thanks Richard. dsb == dashboard, this was how I remembered the new name, Isn't this proving how hard to remember it. ;-) I guess osd == openstask_dashboard? I am glad someone like it. :) hopefully others feel comfortable with it, I am not, but won't block it."}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-04-28 16:26:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22: Workflow-1

Sean makes a good point about "hz" not being semantic.  From a semantic point of view ../static/framework is more meaningful than ../static/hz.

Also, looking at the full path, "hz" and "osd" are already represented as a parent directory. If you ignore the "static" directory, the module names and paths line up well with the directory structure.

/horizon/horizon/static/framework/api
hz.framework.api

/horizon/openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/launch-instance
osd.dashboard.launch-instance"

In both cases, the module prefix (hz or osd) is matched to the application level directory, then everything else is semantic. "framework" and "dashboard" serve to group those things that are not other kinds of static resources (like themes or plugins or something)

I think this makes a lot of sense. The downside is that it isn't immediately obvious to a new person why the "framework" level is needed, but it is deducible once you look at openstack_dashboard. I like the general flexibility of Sean's recomendation.

I think it will make even more sense if things like Launch Instance then become "osd.dashboard.launch-instance" where dashboard is roughly a peer to "framework" in "hz.framework".

Refactoring (once again :) ) to /horizon/horizon/static/framework...'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-04-28 16:39:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 22: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

If we look to the johnpapa style guide, all modules should be in their own file.  

https://github.com/johnpapa/angular-styleguide#style-y001

I just put some comments on Thai's patch with some of the same questions.

'}, {'created': '2015-04-22 18:37:56.000000000', 'message': 'Make directory structure match Angular modules

Refactor horizon Angular modules to have a consistent naming
scheme and a matching directory structure.

Change Summary:
- change /horizon/static/angular to /horizon/static/framework
- move hz.framework.* modules to hz.framework.service.*
- move hz.widget.* modules to hz.framework.widget.*
- Lists of module dependencies are now sorted alphabetically.
- Lists of file includes for tests are now sorted alphabetically.
- changed basePath to be hz.framework.*.basePath
- SCSS files are now hierarchical like modules
- change all module and constant names to include package
- unit tests added to check that new constant names correctly defined
- remove unneeded module injections from tests

Change-Id: I8b50460cb447b624520d7bb626c734cf9c34beb2
'}, {'created': '2015-04-22 18:47:04.000000000', 'message': 'Make directory structure match Angular modules

Refactor horizon Angular modules to have a consistent naming
scheme and a matching directory structure.

Change Summary:
- change /horizon/static/angular to /horizon/static/framework
  - "angular" is a technology. "framework" better reflects the
    conceptual structure of the code
- move hz.framework.* modules to hz.framework.service.*
  - "framework" now means things that support the UI
  - "framework.service" are things that are general helpers
    for other components like framework.widget.*
- move hz.widget.* modules to hz.framework.widget.*
- Lists of module dependencies are now sorted alphabetically.
  - order doesn't matter for dependency injection. Alpha sort
    makes it easier to find missing items
- Lists of file includes for tests are now sorted alphabetically.
- changed basePath to be hz.framework.*.basePath
  - "basePath" is too generic, and depends on the module. Fully
    qualifying the name allows nested modules to refine the basePath
- SCSS files are now hierarchical like modules
- change all module and constant names to include package
  - constants live in a global namespace. When constants have a generic
    name like "helpText" it is easy to accidentally get the wrong version
    injected, depending on the order that .js files are parsed. Eliminate
    this source of run-time bugs by explicitly naming constants with the
    module that contains them (hz.framework.widget.transfer-table.helpText)
- unit tests added to check that new constant names correctly defined
- remove unneeded module injections from tests
  - .hz is needed to get the non-standard interpolater "{$". Otherwise
    parent modules do not need to be injected by default unless the test
    directly uses something (like basePath) from that module

Change-Id: I8b50460cb447b624520d7bb626c734cf9c34beb2

'}, {'created': '2015-05-12 19:29:51.000000000', 'message': 'Make directory structure match Angular modules

Refactor horizon Angular modules to have a consistent naming
scheme and a matching directory structure.

Basic theory:
1) /horizon is the root "horizon" module
2) /horizon/horizon/static/framework contains the reusable Angular components
   in the "horizon.framework" module (no specific business logic). These
   components are used to build horizon-based UIs (like openstack_dashboard).
3) /horizon/openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard contains the "core" logic
   for the openstack_dashboard UI in the "horizon.dashboard" module.
4) /horizon/openstack_dashboard/static/hz-app contains the "bootstrap" logic
   for the openstack_dashboard UI, bringing in all required modules for the
   application (namely "horizon.framework" and "horizon.dashboard". In the
   future, this "application" module will likely move out of openstack_dashboard
   and into its own application directory
5) openstack_dashboard/enabled/_10_project.py brings in all the source (other
   than framework) needed by the hz-app application.
6) Directory structure is based on module hierarchy. Code that lives
   in the module "horizon.framework.widget.wizard" is placed in the directory
   horizon/horizon/static/framework/widget/
7) API code move to openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/api to better
   match the location of API support in the Python code

commit_message:
Make directory structure match Angular modules

Refactor horizon Angular modules to have a consistent naming
scheme and a matching directory structure.

Basic theory:
1) /horizon is the root "horizon" module
2) /horizon/horizon/static/framework contains the reusable Angular components
   in the "horizon.framework" module (no specific business logic). These
   components are used to build horizon-based UIs (like openstack_dashboard).
3) /horizon/horizon/static/hz-app contains the "bootstrap" logic
   for the openstack_dashboard UI, bringing in all required modules for the
   application (namely "horizon.framework". In the future, this "application"
   module will likely move out of horizon and into its own application directory
3) /horizon/openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard contains the "core" logic
   for the openstack_dashboard UI in the "horizon.dashboard" module.
5) openstack_dashboard/enabled/_10_project.py brings in all the source
   needed by that specific project dashboard. Source that is used by multiple
   dashboards is currently included using horizon/_scripts.html.
6) Directory structure is based on module hierarchy. Code that lives
   in the module "horizon.framework.widget.wizard" is placed in the directory
   horizon/horizon/static/framework/widget/
7) API code move to openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/api to better
   match the location of API support in the Python code

Change-Id: I8b50460cb447b624520d7bb626c734cf9c34beb2

commit_message:
Fix missing translations for log messages

Fixed log translations in sqlalchemy module for error, info and warning
messages with appropriate marker function according to the logging
standards [1].

As LOG.warn has deprecated [2] so I have changed LOG.warn to
LOG.warning.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html
[2] http://bugs.python.org/issue13235

Partial-Bug: 1431256
Change-Id: Icec6775ca54b47bd0aa7796d5656a0f42a599f51

commit_message:
Enhance dict compat of VersionedObjectDictCompat

Add more dictionary methods to VersionedObjectDictCompat:

 * __iter__()
 * keys(), iterkeys()
 * values(), itervalues()

Thanks to new methods, dict constructor now accepts
VersionedObjectDictCompat: it's possible to write directly dict(obj)
instead of having to write dict(obj.iteritems()).

On Python 3, items() now returns an iterator instead of a list, to
respect Python 3 dictionary API, as the new keys() and values() methods.

Keep iterkeys(), itervalues() and iteritems() on Python 3, even if
Python 3 dictionaries don't have these methods, just to ease the
transition from Python 2 to Python 3 in Nova.

Change-Id: I4c52d44c7ba49f98b1bbd123209fce7b70ade98d

commit_message:
Add functional tests to tox

This adds functional tests to tox, along with a number of prerequisite
steps. Since this is primarily a bash project, pbr usage has been avoided.
Tests are to be written in python and put in the tests directory.

Running tox -e setupenv will execute a setup script
(tests/setup_docker.sh) to ensure the running instance of docker meets
the minimum version requirement.

Running tox -e images will execute the image building script
(tools/build-all-docker-images) and will parse the resulting output to report
failures.

Running tox -e startenv will generate the environment file, run
"tools/kolla start", and run first time initialization (eventually).

Running tox -e functional is for actually testing the deployed OpenStack
environment via a series of tests utilizing the client APIs.

Change-Id: Iff6dfdca43f0c44d471e7540a7836e56a0de4507

commit_message:
Drop outdated notes and docstrings

VersionedObjectDictCompat code come from Nova. While Nova may drop the
dictionary compatibility, dropping a class in a library requires a
deprecation process, so notes are not really usefull.

Remove also useless docstrings: in oslo_versionedobjects, there is no
really "backward compatibility" issue since it's a new library. Again,
docstrings came from Nova, but I consider them useless in this library.

Replace also "compat" with "compatibility" in VersionedObjectDictCompat
docstring.

Change-Id: Ie42e9ef68f3acd657521454ff3cb5fbdc42ad416

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-27 09:39:58.000000000', 'message': 'Use compute_node consistently in ResourceTracker

This is the second step to convert the ResourceTracker compute
node property to be a ComputeNode object.

The methods that calculate resource usage in the ResourceTracker
sometimes work on a dict data structure obtained from the virt
driver by the get_available_resources() method and sometimes
on the compute_node data structure itself, depending on which is
passed in as a parameter. The result of the changes are always
copied into the compute_node.

This mixing of data structures wont work if compute_node is
converted to be a ComputeNode object. The previous patch in this
series created a compute_node at the start of
update_available_resources() so it exists at the outset. This
patch copies the resources data into compute_node and passes that
single data structure to the update methods consistently.

This step will allow us, in following patches, to convert the code
in the update methods to work on the ComputeNode object instead
of an arbitrary dict.

Minor changes included are removal the final copy into
compute_node and moving initialisation of the stats plugin
into _update_available_resource() along side initialistion
of the pci_tracker.

Change-Id: Ia79b34aa9e6aad5cabe63bb7545c545b952b2b3a
'}, {'created': '2015-03-06 16:04:12.000000000', 'message': 'Use compute_node consistently in ResourceTracker

This is the second step to convert the ResourceTracker compute
node property to be a ComputeNode object.

The methods that calculate resource usage in the ResourceTracker
sometimes work on a dict data structure obtained from the virt
driver by the get_available_resources() method and sometimes
on the compute_node data structure itself, depending on which is
passed in as a parameter. The result of the changes are always
copied into the compute_node.

This mixing of data structures wont work if compute_node is
converted to be a ComputeNode object. The previous patch in this
series created a compute_node at the start of
update_available_resources() so it exists at the outset. This
patch copies the resources data into compute_node and passes that
single data structure to the update methods consistently.

This step will allow us, in following patches, to convert the code
in the update methods to work on the ComputeNode object instead
of an arbitrary dict.

Minor changes included are removal the final copy into
compute_node and moving initialisation of the stats plugin
into _update_available_resource() along side initialistion

Change-Id: Ia79b34aa9e6aad5cabe63bb7545c545b952b2b3a
'}, {'created': '2015-03-11 17:08:05.000000000', 'message': 'Use compute_node consistently in ResourceTracker

This is the second patch set in a series refactoring code that
uses ResourceTracker.compute_node so that it can later be changed
to be a ComputeNode object. Note that in this patch compute_node
is still a dict.

The methods that calculate resource usage in the ResourceTracker
take a parameter called (variously) resources, values or stats.
Sometimes these are called passing self.compute_node as the value
for this parameter and sometimes a dict data structure obtained
from the virt driver by the get_available_resources() method.
The result of the changes are always copied into the
self.compute_node.

This mixing of data structures wont work if self.compute_node is
converted to be a ComputeNode object instead of a dict. The
previous patch in this series initialises self.compute_node at
the start of _update_available_resources() so it has a value at
the outset. This patch copies the resources data into
self.compute_node and uses only that data structure in the methods
that calculate resource usage. As a consequence it is no longer
necessary to pass this in as a parameter in those methods or to
copy the result into self.compute_node at the end of the
calculations.

This step will allow us, in following patches, to convert the code
in the update methods to object notiation when self.compute_node
is changed to be an object instread of a dict.

Minor changes included are removal the final copy into
compute_node and moving initialisation of the stats plugin
into _update_available_resource() along side initialistion
of the pci_tracker.

commit_message:
Use compute_node consistently in ResourceTracker

This is the second patch set in a series refactoring code that
uses ResourceTracker.compute_node so that it can later be changed
to be a ComputeNode object. Note that in this patch compute_node
is still a dict.

The methods that calculate resource usage in the ResourceTracker
take a parameter called (variously) resources, values or stats.
Sometimes these are called passing self.compute_node as the value
for this parameter and sometimes a dict data structure obtained
from the virt driver by the get_available_resources() method.
The result of the changes are always copied into the
self.compute_node.

This mixing of data structures won't work if self.compute_node is
converted to be a ComputeNode object instead of a dict. The
previous patch in this series initialises self.compute_node at
the start of _update_available_resources() so it has a value at
the outset. This patch copies the resources data into
self.compute_node and uses only that data structure in the methods
that calculate resource usage. As a consequence it is no longer
necessary to pass this in as a parameter in those methods or to
copy the result into self.compute_node at the end of the
calculations.

This step will allow us, in following patches, to convert the code
in the update methods to object notiation when self.compute_node
is changed to be an object instread of a dict.

Minor changes included are removal the final copy into
compute_node and moving initialisation of the stats plugin
into _init_compute_node().

Change-Id: Ia79b34aa9e6aad5cabe63bb7545c545b952b2b3a

commit_message:
Proof of Concept: read/write functional tests

Fully nova CLI based read/write functional tests. Before this lands
we need to add '--poll' support to several CLI commands (and python
client side) to make things not suck.

Note: I started writing this before
Iaf474298be135843bff0114cf211bee19762f3ad
and wanted to post it, so we can discuss how the functional tests should
look going forward.

Change-Id: Idc67471a32e6a5c3c83154066c6695cd47a2f588
Related-Bug: #1423695

commit_message:
Added more unit-tests to taskmanager

More tests have been added to improve code-coverage
of following code-files:

- trove/taskmanager/api.py
- trove/taskmanager/manager.py
- trove/taskmanager/service.py
- trove/taskmanager/models.py

commit_message:
Added unit-tests for mgmt-cluster-service

Tests have been added to improve code-coverage for:
trove/extensions/mgmt/clusters/service.py

This patchset also removes some bugs:
- trove/extensions/mgmt/clusters/service.py defined
  management cluster controller with the same name
  as was the name of parent class, so updated the name
  from ClusterController to MgmtClusterController
- ClusterController.action had some code paths which would
  have never been executed, so removed them,
  - It has scope of only one action but still has the code to raise exception
    if multiple actions specified,
    this was probably coming from copy from management-instance-controller
    action method which has multiple actions.
- Rewrote the logic to find action from request body,
  since there is only one valid action, so loop is not needed to be
  traversed to check through the body for invalid requested action.

Change-Id: I8fc3c08c51b4e35a7aa47bd93a8743e22cbf8c75
Closes-Bug: #1452455

commit_message:
Support for specifying segmentation id optional

This fix for supporting the '0' segmentation id during l2gateway connection create.
This is applied for the use case where some bare metal server can not handle tagged packets(connected to access ports)

Closes-Bug:1444188

Change-Id: Ia92432f0296152116e998ad8418c35ef014f898e

commit_message:
Switch tempest python 3.4 unit test job to gating

This commit switches the tempest unit test job which was previously
experimental to run as gating. The unit tests are now working under
python 3.4 so lets make this job voting to prevent that from
regressing.

Change-Id: I6ce20d90ddba1b0b2f094f546a1ee7f85bcef6d1
Depends-On: Icf9090df83f8266a4683c88995c547e3c1bff523

commit_message:
Use six.moves.builtins to mock open in unit tests

This commit switches all the mocks for the open call to use the six
builtins module instead of __builtin__. This is needed because on
python 3 it was renamed to builtins, so to enable running the unit
tests on either environment we need to leverage the six module.

Change-Id: Idf8c0e9858451507c9ac0cfae747f90c6feb7f1e

Member has subnet_id and we need to compare with network_id.
In order to do this CalculateDelta task now takes in a load balancer
loops through the amphora, collects the plugged networks
and gathers the network_ids from member subnet_ids and
builds the list accordingly.

Updates network_tasks CalculateDelta
Updates driver adding method to get network
Updates tests and other required code

commit_message:
Updates for calculate delta task

Member has subnet_id and we need to compare with network_id.
In order to do this CalculateDelta task now takes in a load balancer
loops through the amphora, collects the plugged networks
and gathers the network_ids from member subnet_ids and
builds the list accordingly.

Updates network_tasks CalculateDelta
Updates network_tasks adding method to handle deltas
Updates driver adding method to get network
Updates tests, spec and other required code

Change-Id: I698625e4e2e7352cb3000e22de808c33fa7636ed

There's a new utility in pypowervm that'll produce a sanitized file name from any input.  Given that, how would you ideally like to see things named?  Here are the various types of things in question, and my initial proposal for naming them:

  o Config drive: 'config_%s.iso' % sanitize(instance.name)
  o Boot disk: 'boot_%s' % sanitize(instance.name)
  o Rescue disk: 'rescue_%s' % sanitize(instance.name)
  o Image: 'image_%s' % sanitize(image.name)"}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-05-12 12:25:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think using the santization method that is in pypowervm makes more sense.  It guarantees correctness.  I personally would prefer names that match the instance name, rather than the UUID.  However, even then there is a chance for name collision (two instances with same name)...

How long is the UUID?  Could we have embed the UUID to the tail end of the instance.name?  Ex.

'config_%s_%s.iso' % sanitize(instance.name), sanitize(instance.uuid)?

Also need to keep in mind that instance names can be long.  So we probably would need to 'trim' off of that."}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-05-12 12:26:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

And I'm also wondering if what I just stated here also applies to the instance name we use for the VM itself."}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-05-12 22:36:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We have 79 chars to play with, so it would usually be possible to include both the instance name and UUID in the disk name string.  However, the instance name currently already has a quarter of the UUID in it.  That alone should make the probability of collisions negligible.'}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-05-12 22:46:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-12 22:53:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Sanitize config ISO name

Previously, we were using the instance's name verbatim to generate the
name of its config ISO.  Since the format of the instance name is very
permissive, this can lead to rejection of the name by the PowerVM REST
API:

Value 'Linux Test_0ce757b1_thorst_config.iso' is not facet-valid with
respect to pattern '([A-Za-z0-9_\.]{1,79})' for type 'FileName.Pattern'.

This change set exploits a new pypowervm utility to sanitize the
instance name and combine it with the desired prefix and suffix to
generate a valid config ISO name.

The same is being done for an instance's boot/rescue disks and image LUs
(for SSP).

Change-Id: Id8a77e20ede3ec3339ef5e5910e05943683a2b6c

commit_message:
Add packages required for iscsi extension in agent

In Kilo, we added added an iscsi extension in
ironic-python-agent which requires tgtd and tgtadm.
This commit adds scsi-target-utils to the ramdisk for
this.

Also the git protocol for retrieving the source code is
changed to http.  Git protocol doesn't go through a proxy,
but http can.

Closes-Bug: 1449854
Change-Id: I8cf274913a16404941770d0c6115bd6feec1ccb8

commit_message:
Allow Magnum to conform to global requirements process

Magnum recently entered the openstack/ namespace from
stackforge. So Magnum would like to conform to the
global requirements process. To be able to do that,
We need docker-py library in our global requirements.

docker-py library is actively maintained at:
https://github.com/docker/docker-py/

docker-py is licensed as:
Apache License, Version 2.0

docker-py various python flavors including 3.4:
https://travis-ci.org/docker/docker-py

We also do not have any other libraries in our
global requirements that provide this functionality.

Change-Id: Ic64996120a3a108b9b6d3c8daa313ea654fedba4

commit_message:
Create split out neutron networks via Heat.

This patch adds a new abstraction for network creation
within Heat. This (optional) set of templates may be disabled
if you wish to create Neutron networks for the undercloud
via Heat templates... instead of using os-cloud-config
JSON to do so. Creating networks with Heat has the benefit
of being parameter driven so that users can quickly
enable networks using the resource registry and parameters.

There are 5 networks to start with which are roughly modeled
around networks an Overcloud user might want to use to isolate
their traffic. The intent is to make these opt-in and
configurable for end users.

The networks.yaml template can be used to create all of the
networks using parameters in the resource registry.

Change-Id: I5f2b3356378eb263d90d428cc83c7f5b141957e1

commit_message:
Add kilo compat jobs to tempest and devstack-gate

Since the kilo release we need to verify that tempest and devstack-gate
master works with a stable/kilo cloud for incoming commits. This commit
adds the missing stable/kilo compat jobs to check this.

Change-Id: I3b1277aac985f7b072f26b8c4a3e426c22325312

commit_message:
Move ebrctl to compute.filter.

Currently ebrctl is network.filters, but the utility is
used by libvirt in nova compute, as part of a Mellanox vif driver.

The ubuntu packages install network.filters with the nova-network package.
But this vif driver only works with Neutron.

To help fix that, this patch move it to compute.filters to ensure it is
always installed with Nova.

Closes-Bug: #1453418

Change-Id: Ib61a565c10edfa662c15fac339b2cbd9bb673631

commit_message:
Authenticate the domain user with id instead of username

This change makes the authentication process that requests a domain user
token provide user_id and password instead of username and password.
Authenticating with the user_id is more reliable, as that works even when
the username is truncated or modified in any other way before it is passed
to Keystone.

Conflicts:
	heat/common/heat_keystoneclient.py

Change-Id: I7b2897c2be1e4ad7f55549449b1791991572a7f1
Closes-bug: 1402894
(cherry picked from commit 0ba4dacbe292a182ac4ccd69f1133aa6cdba8045)

commit_message:
Tell stevedore not to force verify requirements

Disable the strict requirements checking in pkg_resources by telling
stevedore to bypass it. This avoids issues with devstack configurations
where the "wrong" version of a library is installed, even though it is
functional.

Closes-Bug: #1454572
Change-Id: Idbdbdd2548ad39325d8058eb19ee398f732c2e44

commit_message:
Spawn RADVD only in the master HA router

Currently radvd is spawned in all the HA routers irrespective of the
state of the router. This approach has the following issues.

1. While processing the internal router ports (i.e., qr-xxx), ha_router
   removes the LLA of the interface and adds it as a VIP to Keepalived conf.
   Radvd daemon is spawned after this operation in the router namespace
   (if the port is associated with any IPv6 subnets). Radvd notices that
   qr-xxx interface does not have the LLA, so does not transmit any Router
   Advts. In this state, VMs fail to acquire IPv6 addresses because of the
   missing RAs. Radvd does not recover even after keepalived configures the
   LLA of the interface. The only solution is to restart/reload radvd daemon.
   Currently keepalived-state-change monitor does not do any radvd related
   operations when a state transition happens. So we endup in this state
   forever.
2. For all the routers in Backup state, qr-xxx interface does not have LLA
   as it is managed by keepalived and configured only on the Master HA router.
   In such agents syslog is flooded with the messages [1] and this can cause
   loss of other useful info.
   [1] - resetting ipv6-allrouters membership on qr-2e373555-97

This patch implements the following.
1. If the router is already in the Master state, we configure the LLA as a VIP
   in keepalived conf but do not delete the LLA of the internal interface.
2. We spawn radvd only if the router is in the Master State.
3. Keepalived-state-change monitor takes care of enabling/disabling radvd upon
   state transitions.

Closes-Bug: #1440699
Change-Id: I351c71d058170265bbb8b56e1f7a3430bd8828d5
(cherry picked from commit 2f9b0ce940099bcc82d2940b99bdc387db22d6fc)

commit_message:
Fix last unit tests on py34

This commit fixes the last remaining issues in the tempest unit tests.
There were several failures for a couple of different issues previously
but after this running the tempest unit tests will pass on python 3.4.

Change-Id: Icf9090df83f8266a4683c88995c547e3c1bff523

[{'created': '2015-03-11 16:06:47.000000000', 'message': "Add exception_to_unicode() function

There is no simple way working on Python 2 and Python 3 to get the
message of an exception as a Unicode string. This new functions uses an
heuristic to get the encoding of the exception message. It tries UTF-8
(which is a superset of ASCII), the locale encoding, or fallback to
ISO-8859-1 (which never fails).

This function is required to log exceptions using the logging module
when the exception message contains non-ASCII characters.

- logging.log() only works with non-ASCII characters on Python 2 and
  Python 3 if the message is formatted as Unicode. For example,
  logging.log(b'error: %s', b'\xe9') fails in most cases.
- unicode % bytes doesn't work with non-ASCII characters
- logging.log(u'error: %s', exc) doesn't work if the exception message
  contains a non-ASCII character

Only logging.log(u'error: %s', exception_to_unicode(exc)) works in all
cases: ASCII or non-ASCII exception message, Python 2 and Python 3.

Change-Id: I241b7c81c7ae3d26f81790e9180678dc9af81e22

commit_message:
Add exception_to_unicode() function

There is no simple way working on Python 2 and Python 3 to get the
message of an exception as a Unicode string. This new functions uses an
heuristic to get the encoding of the exception message. It tries UTF-8
(which is a superset of ASCII), the locale encoding, or fallback to
ISO-8859-1 (which never fails).

This function is required to log exceptions using the logging module
when the exception message contains non-ASCII characters.

- logging.log() only works with non-ASCII characters on Python 2 and
  Python 3 if the message is formatted as Unicode. For example,
  logging.log(b'error: %s', b'\xe9') fails in most cases.
- unicode % bytes doesn't work with non-ASCII characters
- logging.log(u'error: %s', exc) doesn't work if the exception message
  contains a non-ASCII character

Only logging.log(u'error: %s', exception_to_unicode(exc)) works in all
cases: ASCII or non-ASCII exception message, Python 2 and Python 3.

Co-Authored-By: Joshua Harlow <harlowja@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I241b7c81c7ae3d26f81790e9180678dc9af81e22

commit_message:
Update vscsi mapping to not include adapter

This change updates the vscsi.py to not send the adapter down when
requesting that the scsi adapter be connected.  This was due to a recent
change in pypowervm, and the refactor was missed in the nova-powervm
code.

An additional unit test was added to cover this.

Change-Id: Ic8555f49f213e3e7e46a59e1518984ef5e0f431b

commit_message:
Denote monotonic import ordering + usage

In the stop watch class docstring denote which
monotonic functions will be imported and in what
order and how the final fallback will use the non
monotonic time.time.

Change-Id: Iecaf256d4322c7d96348d8a4e9612d5f8e18c94e

commit_message:
Provide an API to let tempest control the log file

By default we log to stdout, but tempest wants to provide a log
file. Because tempest doesn't use a configuration file, there's no easy
way for them to give us a filename to use. We don't want most projects
to set a programmatic default, so rather than adding this to
set_defaults(), we define a new function and document that only tempest
should call it.

Change-Id: I1d4919ae1bb810931ac06226165bbf1f31e25417

commit_message:
rabbit: smarter declaration of the notif. queue

The NotifyPublisher was redeclaring again and again,
the same exchange and queue each times a notification is sent.

This change fixes that by caching the already declared exchange
and queue for each channel.

Also, to make the test pass. 'Connection.ensure' have been updated
to have the same behavior for amqp and memory driver about
kombu recoverable_errors. And the hostname and port of the memory
driver are set to not fail when we print a log message.

Closes bug: #1437902

Change-Id: I20d133ac67b8a8a4c51d51b6a1b2369aa44ffe2f

commit_message:
rabbit: redeclare consumers when ack/requeue fail

In case the acknowledgement or requeue of a message fail,
the kombu transport can be disconnected

In this case, we must redeclare our consumers.

This changes fixes that.

This have no tests because the kombu memory transport we use in our tests
cannot be in disconnected state.

Closes-bug: #1448650

Change-Id: I5991a4cf827411bc27c857561d97461212a17f40
